Alan Walker, *Fryderyk Chopin: A Life and Times* (Farrar, Straus and Giroux, 2018). Standard modern biography.

Arthur Hedley, ed. and trans., *Selected Correspondence of Fryderyk Chopin* (Heinemann, 1962; revised McGraw-Hill 1963).

For the Field origin of the term 'nocturne': see Grove entry above and Nicholas Temperley, *John Field* (Cambridge University Press, 1988).

Scores of Op. 9, Op. 18, Op. 27, and Op. 48 are all in the public domain and available on IMSLP.\"

  :notes
\"All opus numbers, keys, dates, dedicatees, and structural claims are verifiable in Grove and Walker. The Field-invented-the-nocturne claim is the standard scholarly account. The Rubinstein and Horowitz recordings of Op. 48 No. 1 are verifiable in their discographies. The pedagogical Scheme example is not a transcription of any specific Chopin piece — it is a texture study inspired by the twelve-eight nocturne pattern, honestly labeled as such.\"

  :philosopher-weave-details
\"Jung: the small piece as an object, self-contained, complete unto itself.
Peirce: the nocturne as icon of a night (resemblance), of a mood (index), and of the genre (symbol).
Wittgenstein-late: the nocturne as a form of life pianists share — you learn what a nocturne IS by hearing many of them.
Freud: the ornament as the return of the theme — you meet the tune plainly, then meet it again decorated, and the second meeting reads over the first.
Aristotle: the small arc, complete in itself — a beginning, a middle, an end within seven minutes.\"

  :tie-forward
\"Chapter 13 will name and inhabit three of the large forms — sonata form, rondo, theme and variations — so we can pick them out when we hear them and use them when we write.\")
